The '''Blackburn Female Reform Society''' was established in early July 1819.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/893558457|title=Return to Peterloo|last=Poole|first=Robert|publisher=Carnegie|others=|year=2014|isbn=9781859362259|location=Lancaster|pages=49|oclc=893558457}}</ref> They immediately sent a circular to other districts, inviting the wives and daughters of the workmen in the different branches of manufacturing to form themselves into similar societies. In response Manchester formed their own [[Manchester Female Reform Society|society of reformers]] on 20 July 1819.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wooler|first=T. J.|date=4 August 1819|title=The Manchester Female Reformers address to the wives, mothers, sisters and daughters of the higher and middling classes of society|url=|journal=The Black Dwarf|volume=31|pages=|via=}}</ref>
