==Prehistoric settlement== [[File:Pre-clovis-sites-of-the-americas.svg|thumb|Map of the Americas showing pre Clovis sites.]] {{Main article|Settlement of the Americas}} {{See also|Clovis culture}} * '''16,000 years before present''': In the 20th century it was generally believed that humans has crossed a land bridge from [[Eurasia]] perhaps 12,000 years ago &mdash; the 'Clovis First / Single origin hypothesis' &mdash; but modern scientific belief is that settlers arrived by boat at least 14,000-16,000 years before present.
==Norse colonization== {{Main article|Norse colonization of the Americas}} * '''c. 1000''': [[Erik the Red]] and [[Leif Ericson]], Viking navigators, discovered and settled [[Greenland]], ''[[Helluland]]'' (possibly [[Baffin Island]]), ''[[Markland]]'', now called [[Labrador]] and [[Vinland]], now called [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]]). The Greenland colony lasted until the 15th century, but the settlement at [[L'Anse aux Meadows]] is the only known [[Norsemen|Norse]] villages in North America outside of Greenland. This was estimated to have endured less than a decade. * '''c. 1350''': The Norse [[History of Greenland#Norse settlement|Western Settlement]] in Greenland was abandoned. * '''1354''': King [[Magnus IV of Sweden|Magnus of Sweden and Norway]] authorised [[Paul Knutson]] to lead an expedition to Greenland which may never have taken place * '''c.1450–1480s''':{{sfn|Seaver|1996|p=205, 229|ps=: 205: a reference to sailors in Bergen in 1484 who had visited Greenland (Seaver speculates that they may have been English); 229: archaeological evidence of contact with Europe towards the end of the 15th century.}} The Norse [[History of Greenland#Norse settlement|Eastern Settlement]] in Greenland was abandoned during the opening stages of the [[Little Ice Age#Northern Hemisphere|Little Ice Age]].
